sessment with stipulated consequences could lead to major improvements in schools. This was accomplished politically by proclaiming lofty goals of attaining universal proficiency and closing achievement gaps, which repeatedly failed to materialize. But even after very clear disappointments, no other policy framework has emerged to challenge its hegemony. The American public today has little confidence in institutions to improve the quality of goods and services they provide, especially in the public sector. As a consequence, many Americans continue to believe that accountability remains a vital necessity, even if educators and policy scholars disagree.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAcademic achievementzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEducationxStandardszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEducational accountabilityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSchool improvement programszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, policy, government, academia, teaching, learning, school, schooling, standardized testing, testing, SAT, ACT, assessment.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079131040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883231240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978832312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978832312/original  a978-3-11-079131-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles